493	/// The per-cell fit **budgets** of one record group (all premises together, or all
494	/// conclusions together): the cells share the group's [`FILL_WIDTH`] budget
495	/// (BEHAVIOR.md §3f), and each cell is then laid out INDEPENDENTLY at its budget by
496	/// the faithful pretty-printer ([`crate::doclayout`]). A single budget per cell
497	/// (the exact engine turns it into the wrap decision AND the ragged fill packing —
498	/// no separate trigger/fill split is needed once the fitting is faithful).
499	///
500	/// The budgets are a **proportional** allocation of the group's [`FILL_WIDTH`]:
501	/// cell *i* gets `round(87 · flat_i / T)` where `T = Σ flat_j` is the group's flat
502	/// width, floored at [`MIN_CELL_BUDGET`]. This distributes the shared row width in
503	/// proportion to each cell's content — the model the corpus census selects (81 %
504	/// of wrapping cells byte-exact; 94.7 % of single-cell groups, whose budget is 87
505	/// since `T = flat`). Consequences:
506	///   * a group whose total fits (`T ≤ 87`) gives every cell `≥ flat_i` → nothing
507	///     wraps;
508	///   * the Wide-rule conclusion group `[Ack 25, Big 68, Out 11]` (`T = 104`):
509	///     `Ack` gets `round(87·25/104) = 21` (wraps), `Big` `round(87·68/104) = 57`
510	///     (eight tuple elements on line 0), `Out` `round(87·11/104) = 9 → 20` (fits);
511	///   * the `20` floor is the observed per-cell minimum (a cell of flat ≤ 20 never
512	///     wraps).
513	///
514	/// Residual (honest): the true per-cell coupling is the reference pretty-printer's
515	/// own `fits` over the whole group, which proportional approximates to within a
516	/// few columns; the ~20 % of multi-cell wrapping cells that miss are that ±few-
517	/// column bucket boundary plus cells whose wrap is decided on their un-abbreviated
518	/// width (BEHAVIOR.md §3f) — beyond a rendering crate that receives post-
519	/// abbreviation cell text.
520	pub fn group_widths(widths: &[usize]) -> Vec<usize> {
521	    let t: usize = widths.iter().sum();
522	    if t == 0 {
523	        return vec![FILL_WIDTH as usize; widths.len()];
524	    }
525	    let full = FILL_WIDTH as usize;
526	    widths
527	        .iter()
528	        .map(|&f| {
529	            // round(87 * f / T)
530	            let b = (full * f + t / 2) / t;
